"Ma Q., Liu Y., He H.","The utilization of physisorption analyzer for studying the hygroscopic properties of atmospheric relevant particles",2010,"Journal of Physical Chemistry A","114","12",,"4232","4237",,,10.1021/jp909340v,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77950240542&partnerID=40&md5=994766680080a8b869882b5ff51be9e5","State Key Laboratory of Environmental Chemistry and Ecotoxicology, Research Center for Eco-Environmental Sciences, Chinese Academy of Sciences, 18 Shuangqing Road, Haidian District, Beijing 100085, China","Ma, Q., State Key Laboratory of Environmental Chemistry and Ecotoxicology, Research Center for Eco-Environmental Sciences, Chinese Academy of Sciences, 18 Shuangqing Road, Haidian District, Beijing 100085, China; Liu, Y., State Key Laboratory of Environmental Chemistry and Ecotoxicology, Research Center for Eco-Environmental Sciences, Chinese Academy of Sciences, 18 Shuangqing Road, Haidian District, Beijing 100085, China; He, H., State Key Laboratory of Environmental Chemistry and Ecotoxicology, Research Center for Eco-Environmental Sciences, Chinese Academy of Sciences, 18 Shuangqing Road, Haidian District, Beijing 100085, China","The hygroscopic behavior of atmospheric aerosols has a significant effect on the global climate change. In this study, a physisorption analyzer was used to measure the water adsorption capacity of Al2O3, NaCl, NH4NO3, and (NH4)2SO4 particles at 273.6 K. Qualitative and quantitative information about water adsorption on these particles was obtained with changing the temperature and/or relative humidity (RH). Uptake of water on Al2O3 showed a type-II BET adsorption isotherm with the monolayer formed at ∼18% relative humidity (RH). The hygroscopic properties of NaCl, (NH4) 2SO4, and NH4NO3, including the deliquescence relative humidities (DRH), the temperature dependence of the DRH for NH4NO3, and the growth factors of NaCl and (NH 4)2SO4 were determined. All these results were in good agreement with the results obtained by other methods and/or theoretical prediction with a deviation less than 2%. For NaCl, the water adsorption amount increase rate exhibits three stages (&lt;30% RH, ∼30%-65% RH, and &gt;65% RH) in the predeliquescence process and monolayer thin film water was formed at about 30% RH. It demonstrated that this instrument was practicable for studying the hygroscopic behavior of both soluble and insoluble but wettable atmospheric nonviolate aerosol particles. © 2010 American Chemical Society.",,"Aerosol particles; Global climate changes; Growth factor; Hygroscopic behavior; Hygroscopic properties; Quantitative information; Relative humidities; Temperature dependence; Theoretical prediction; Thin film water; Three stages; Water adsorption; Water adsorption capacity; Atmospheric aerosols; Climate change; Dewatering; Moisture; Monolayers; Physisorption; Sodium chloride; Atmospheric humidity",,,,,,"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AerosolPandis, S.N., Wexler, A.S., Seinfeld, J.H., (1995) J. Phys. Chem., 99 (24), pp. 9646-9659; Summary for policymakers (2007) Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis. Contribution of Working Group i to the Fourth Assessment Report of the IntergoVernmental Panel on Climate Change, pp. 1-18. , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) Solomon, S., et al., Eds.; Cambridge University Press: New York, 2007; Ramanathan, V., Crutzen, P.J., Kiehl, J.T., Rosenfeld, D., (2001) Science, 294, pp. 2119-2124; Pilinis, C., Pandis, S.N., Seinfeld, J.H., (1995) J. Geophys. Res., 100 (D9), pp. 18739-18754; Pruppacher, H.R., Klett, J.D., (1997) Microphysics of Clouds and Precipitation, , Kluwer Academic: Norwell, MA; Charlson, R.J., Schwartz, S.E., Hales, J.M., Cess, R.D., Coakley Jr., J.A., Hansen, J.E., Hofmann, D.J., (1992) Science, 255, pp. 423-430; Gibson, E.R., Hudson, P.K., Grassian, V.H., (2006) J. Phys. Chem. A, 110 (42), pp. 11785-11799; Cwiertny, D.M., Young, M.A., Grassian, V.H., (2008) Annu. Rev. Phys. Chem., 59, pp. 27-51; Orr Jr., C., Hurd, F.K., Hendrix, W.P., Junge, C., (1958) J. Meteorol., 15, pp. 240-242; Rader, D.J., McMurry, P.H., (1986) J. Aerosol Sci., 17 (5), pp. 771-787; Weingartner, E., Gysel, M., Baltensperger, U., (2002) EnViron. Sci. Technol., 36 (1), pp. 55-62; Cruz, C.N., Pandis, S.N., (2000) EnViron. Sci. Technol., 34 (20), pp. 4313-4319; Hämeri, K., Laaksonen, A., Vakeva, M., Suni, T., (2001) J. Geophy. Res., 106 (D18), pp. 20749-20757; Joutsensaari, J., Vaattovaara, P., Vesterinen, M., Hämeri, K., Laaksonen, A., (2001) Atmos. Chem. Phys., 1, pp. 51-60; Tang, I.N., Munkelwitz, H.R., (1993) Atmos. EnViron., 27 A (4), pp. 467-473; Cohen, M.D., Flagan, R.C., Seinfeld, J.H., (1987) J. Phys. Chem., 91 (17), pp. 4563-4574; Chan, C.K., Ha, Z., Choi, M.Y., (2000) Atmos. EnViron., 34, pp. 4795-4803; Cziczo, D.J., Abbatt, J.P.D., (2000) J. Phys. Chem. A, 104 (10), pp. 2038-2047; Schuttlefield, J., Al-Hosney, H., Zachariah, A., Grassian, V.H., (2007) Appl. Spectrosc., 61, pp. 283-292; Gustafsson, R.J., Orlov, A., Badger, C.L., Griffiths, P.T., Cox, R.A., Lambert, R.M., (2005) Atmos. Chem. Phys., 5, pp. 3415-3421; Foster, M.C., Ewing, G.E., (2000) J. Chem. Phys., 112 (15), pp. 6817-6826; Zhang, Y.H., Chan, C.K., (2002) J. Phys. Chem. A, 106 (2), pp. 285-292; Liu, Y.J., Zhu, T., Zhao, D.F., Zhang, Z.F., (2008) Atmos. Chem. Phys., 8, pp. 7205-7215; Ebert, M., Inerle-Hof, M., Weinbruch, S., (2002) Atmos. EnViron., 36, pp. 5909-5916; Krueger, B.J., Grassian, V.H., Iedema, M.J., Cowin, J.P., Laskin, A., (2003) Anal. Chem., 75 (19), pp. 5170-5179; Dai, Q., Hu, J., Salmeron, M., (1997) J. Phys. Chem. B, 101 (1), pp. 1994-1998; Wise, M.E., Biskos, G., Martin, S.T., Russell, L.M., Buseck, P.R., (2005) Aerosol Sci. Technol., 39, pp. 849-856; Swietlicki, E., Hansson, H.-C., Hameri, K., Svenningsson, B., Massling, A., Mcfiggans, G., McMurry, P.H., Kulmala, M., (2008) Tellus, 60 B, pp. 432-469; Goodman, A.L., Bernard, E.T., Grassian, V.H., (2001) J. Phys. Chem. A, 105 (26), pp. 6443-64